<section xml:id="sec_radical_functions">
  <title>Radical Functions</title>
  <p>
    For your first commands, you should know how to type a square root or other root into Maple.
    The <c>sqrt()</c> command can be used for square roots, while it is usually better to use <c>surd()</c> for higher roots.
  </p>
  <console prompt="> ">
    <input>sqrt(a);</input>
  </console>
  <p>
    <idx><h>mathematical functions</h><h>square root</h></idx>
    <me>
      \displaystyle  \sqrt{a}
    </me>
  </p>
  <aside>
    <p>
      The <c>sqrt()</c> command can also be found in the Expression palette by clicking <m>\sqrt{a}</m>.
      However, the <c>surd()</c> command is better than using the <m>\sqrt[n]{a}</m> button in most cases.
    </p>
  </aside>
  <console prompt="> ">
    <input>surd(a, 3);</input>
  </console>
  <p>
    <idx><h>mathematical functions</h><h>nth root@<m>n</m>th root</h></idx>
    <me>
      \displaystyle \sqrt [3]{a}
    </me>
  </p>
  <console prompt="> ">
    <input>surd(a, 4);</input>
  </console>
  <p>
    <me>
      \displaystyle \sqrt [4]{a}
    </me>
  </p>
  <aside>
    <p>
      Note that capitalization is important in Maple.
      Capitalizing a character that is not supposed to be capitalized will result in an error or useless output.
    </p>
  </aside>
</section>